
[1]rebel

   REB'EL, n. [L. rebellis, making war again.]

   1. One who revolts from the government to which he owes allegiance,
   either by openly renouncing the authority of that government, or by
   taking arms and openly opposing it. A rebel differs from an enemy, as
   the latter is one who does not owe allegiance to the government which
   he attacks. Num. 17.

   2. One who willfully violates a law.

   3. One who disobeys the king's proclamation; a contemner of the king's
   laws.

   4. A villain who disobeys his lord.

                  REB'EL, a. Rebellious; acting in revolt.
